  subhead="A stove installer WhatsApps at 7:15am on a Tuesday with a photo of a fireplace opening. He is fitting a Contura 556 freestanding wood burner in a 1920s detached house in North Oxford — the existing clay liner has been CCTV-surveyed and two sections are cracked with mortar joints displaced. The smoke test failed. His message: 'Morning — need a reline for a Contura 556 install in North Oxford. 1920s detached, existing clay liner cracked in two places, smoke test failed. CCTV report attached. Need a 6-inch 316 flex liner, about 10 metres from pot to register plate, insulated with vermiculite backfill. I am fitting the stove Friday — can your team line Wednesday or Thursday? Need HETAS installation cert for the liner.' You are loading the van with scaffolding for a chimney rebuild in Witney — a three-chimney Georgian townhouse with stacks that need repointing above the roofline. Without AI WhatsApp, the lining request waits until midday when you arrive at Witney. Another liner specialist confirms by 8am. With it, the AI responds at 7:16am, confirms your 316 lining capability, and asks whether the existing pot is serviceable or needs replacing when the liner terminates. The installer confirms the pot is sound. At 9am you review: North Oxford 1920s detached, 316 flex 6-inch 10m, vermiculite, Contura 556, clay cracked in two places, smoke test failed, CCTV report attached, line Wednesday or Thursday, HETAS cert, pot okay."
